<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN"
  "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<!--
  com.apple.Boot.plist — LunaOS arm64 Apple Silicon boot configuration

  ARM64 BOOT CHAIN (very different from x86_64):
  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════

  x86_64 chain:
    BIOS/EFI → GRUB2 → mach_kernel → launchd

  arm64 Apple Silicon chain:
    iBoot (Apple ROM, cannot modify)
      → boot.efi (Apple bootloader, in EFI partition)
        → kernelcache (XNU + prelinked KEXTs)
          → launchd

  KEY DIFFERENCE: iBoot is Apple's Stage 1 bootloader burned into the
  Apple Silicon chip. It is NOT replaceable like GRUB is on x86_64.
  iBoot verifies boot.efi's signature before loading it.

  On LunaOS, we bypass iBoot's signature check via:
    1. DFU mode + idevicerestore (for development)
    2. OR: boot under macOS, then kexec into LunaOS kernel (experimental)
    3. OR: use m1n1 (Asahi Linux's stage 2 bootloader) as an intermediate

  RECOMMENDED TEST APPROACH: QEMU
  ════════════════════════════════
  Use QEMU's virt machine (not real Apple Silicon) for testing:
    qemu-system-aarch64 -M virt -cpu cortex-a76
  This loads the kernel directly, bypassing iBoot entirely.
  No real Apple Silicon hardware needed until the OS is stable.

  PRODUCTION APPROACH (real Apple Silicon):
  ══════════════════════════════════════════
  Integrate with m1n1 (https://github.com/AsahiLinux/m1n1):
    m1n1 is a bootloader that runs after iBoot on Apple Silicon Macs
    configured in "1 True Recovery" or "Permissive Security" mode.
    It loads U-Boot or directly loads kernels.
    The Asahi Linux team has already done this work for Linux — LunaOS
    can use the same m1n1 integration.

  BOOT ARGS for Apple Silicon (subset of x86_64 — some don't apply):
  ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  amfi_get_out_of_my_way=1    — disable AMFI (Apple Mobile File Integrity)
                                CRITICAL on arm64: without this, IODRMShim won't load
  csr-active-config=0xFF      — disable SIP (same as x86_64)
  kext-dev-mode=1             — allow developer KEXTs
  cs_enforcement_disable=1    — disable code signing enforcement
  -v                          — verbose boot
  pmuflags=1                  — disable power management restrictions
  PE_i_can_has_debugger=1     — enable kernel debugging via serial
  serial=3                    — enable serial output (useful in QEMU)
-->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <key>Kernel</key>
    <!-- arm64: kernelcache (prelinked) preferred over raw mach_kernel -->
    <string>kernelcache</string>

    <key>Kernel Flags</key>
    <!-- arm64 CRITICAL: amfi_get_out_of_my_way=1 required for unsigned KEXTs -->
    <string>amfi_get_out_of_my_way=1 csr-active-config=0xFF kext-dev-mode=1 cs_enforcement_disable=1 -v pmuflags=1 serial=3 PE_i_can_has_debugger=1</string>

    <key>Graphics Mode</key>
    <!-- Apple Silicon Retina: use logical resolution (physical is 2x) -->
    <string>2560x1600x32</string>

    <key>Timeout</key>
    <string>3</string>

    <key>OSVersion</key>
    <string>LunaOS 0.1.0 (Darwin 26 / arm64)</string>

    <key>Hibernate Mode</key>
    <integer>0</integer>

    <!--
      arm64 specific: Apple Silicon memory layout
      Kernel loads at 0xfffffff007004000 (KASLR base for arm64)
      Physical memory starts at 0x200000000 on Apple Silicon
    -->
    <key>BootKCPath</key>
    <string>/System/Library/Kernels/kernelcache</string>
</dict>
</plist>
